<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "What is FTP in cycling?", answer: "FTP (Functional Threshold Power) is the highest power output a cyclist can sustain for approximately one hour. It is measured in watts and represents the boundary between sustainable and unsustainable exercise intensity. FTP is the cornerstone of power-based training because all seven Coggan training zones are defined as percentages of this value." },
  { question: "How do I test my FTP?", answer: "The most common FTP test is the 20-minute test: warm up, ride as hard as you can sustain for 20 minutes, and multiply your average power by 0.95. Other methods include the 8-minute test (average power x 0.90) and the ramp test (75% of highest 1-minute power). A true 60-minute test is the gold standard but is extremely demanding and rarely done." },
  { question: "What are the Coggan power zones?", answer: "The Coggan system defines 7 power zones: Zone 1 Active Recovery (less than 55% FTP), Zone 2 Endurance (56-75%), Zone 3 Tempo (76-90%), Zone 4 Lactate Threshold (91-105%), Zone 5 VO2max (106-120%), Zone 6 Anaerobic Capacity (121-150%), and Zone 7 Neuromuscular Power (above 150%). Each zone targets different energy systems and physiological adaptations." },
  { question: "What is a good watts per kg for cycling?", answer: "Watts per kg (W/kg) is FTP divided by body weight in kilograms. Cat 5 recreational riders are typically 2.0-2.8 W/kg, Cat 4 riders 2.8-3.4, Cat 3 riders 3.4-4.0, Cat 2 riders 4.0-4.6, Cat 1/Elite riders 4.6-5.5, and World Tour professionals exceed 5.5 W/kg. These values apply to 1-hour power output." },
  { question: "How often should I retest my FTP?", answer: "Most coaches recommend retesting FTP every 6-8 weeks, or whenever you notice your training zones no longer feel appropriate. After a training block focused on threshold work, you may see significant FTP improvements. Consistently update your zones to ensure training remains at the correct intensity for continued adaptation." }
]) %>

